John,

This shouldn&#39;t be too hard, although it&#39;ll require a little hacking.  If 
it were my task, I&#39;d first write a class that instantiates a TestCase 
for a single method:

void main(String[] argv) {
    TestResult result = new TestResult();
    TestCase case = Class.forName(argv[0]).newInstance(argv[1]);
    case.run(result);
    // output result somehow
}

Then, you can create a wrapper that invokes this for each test you&#39;re 
interested in.  Is that a start?

    David Saff

johnlukar wrote:

&gt;
&gt; Is this possible ?
&gt;
&gt; My problem is that I have a Unit test that does performance
&gt; benchmarking of a product.
&gt;
&gt; Each test method tests one aspect of the product.  The problem is the
&gt; VM performs full GC collection due to the memory being chewed up in a
&gt; single VM invocation that runs all testMethods. 
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; This subsequently results in erronous perfromance times and stats.
&gt;
&gt; so I&#39;d like to run each testMethod in its own VM, and to avoid
&gt; multiple parallel test methods running and chewing up the memory, I
&gt; think I need to run the methods in order.
&gt;
&gt; any ideas ?
&gt;
&gt; thanks much in advance for info.
&gt;
